RELATIONS
accounts ( account_id Pk, client_id Fk , acount_No, account_Type, balance, Status)
bank ( bank_id Pk, bank_Name, established_year, account_id Fk)
client (client_id Pk, fName, mName,lName, phone No., email)
wallet ( wallet_id Pk, balance, client_id Fk)
transaction ( transaction_id Pk, account_id Fk, wallet_id Fk, amount, status, transaction_date, transaction_type, sender_account, receiver_account_id)
authentication (authentication_id Pk, client_id Fk, ip_address, login_time, login_status)
device ( device_id Pk, client_id Fk, device_type, registration_date)
loan ( loan_id Pk, client_id Fk, loan_amount, loan_status, payment_date)

DEPENDENCIES
account_id – client_id, account_no, account_type, balance, status
bank_id – bank_name, established_year, account_Id
client_id - fname, mname, lname, phone_No, email
wallet_Id – balance, client_Id
transaction_id – account_id, wallet_id, amount, status, transaction_date, transaction_type, sender_account_id, receiver_account_id
authentication_id – client_id, ip_address, login_time, login_status
device_id – client_id, device_type, registration_date
loan_id – client_id, loan_amount, loan_status, payment-date

1NF – All relations have primary keys and their attributes cannot be broken further down as they contain one value per cell . Hence all relations are in 1NF.
2NF – All relations have single attribute primary keys, hence no partial dependency exists. Hence all relations are in 2NF.
3NF – There are no transitive dependencies between non-key attributes. Hence relations satisfy 3NF.
